    # [Scene: Wetland Pilot Site | Night]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low wind, the soft slap of water against sandbags, distant gulls calling once and then falling silent]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, steady strings that suggest repair rather than mourning]
    "You kneel in the mud until your knees complain. Your hands are raw where the salt and peat have rubbed the skin away; they smell of wet earth and citrus from the sachets Nova brought to"
    "ward off the biting flies. Every movement is slow and deliberate—push the plug, press the roots into the silt, tamp the soil around the base. The motion steadies the frantic coil in your chest."
    "Samir's voice carries across the shallow channel, rough with instruction and laughter. 'Roots down, eyes up when you can. This mud will take your shoes if you let it, but it won't take the story.' He"
    "grins, water beading on the ends of his dreadlocks. You laugh despite the cold and keep planting."
    "You think of the standoff—a room split along hard lines, Nova like a thunderhead, the mayor's aides with clipboards. The agitation still hums in your jaw, a phantom tide; the difference tonight is that the agitation"
    "has a direction. Here, hands make something that will move the water differently. Here, action stitches possibility into the shoreline."
    show nova_duarte at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nova_duarte "You thought I'd be too loud to build with, didn't you?"
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "I thought you'd be too loud to trust. But then, maybe loudness is a kind of faith."
    "Nova snorts; her eyes hold something complicated—relief, resentment, something like request. She studies the row of young marsh grass as if cataloguing possible futures."

    nova_duarte "Faith that works with a shovel. That's new."
    "You want to say that you're sorry for the moments you hedged, for the times political caution felt like betrayal to people who'd lost houses. You want to say you needed to learn how to move loud into useful. Instead you squeeze the plug into the mud until it holds."
    hide nova_duarte
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The light slap of a wave; someone humming an old market song]
    "Samir guides a small group of neighbors through a rapid-response drill—rope lines, makeshift sand-bag skiffs, the stack of radios that you've been able to procure through a patchwork of favors and fundraisers. His voice is steady, the voice you've always trusted to cut panic into task."
    show samir_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_reyes "Okay, keep the line taut. If the berm takes a hit, we pull the kits and move the elderly to the community center. We do not—repeat—we do not leave anyone behind."
    "A woman from Block C looks at you with eyes rimmed in fatigue. You hand her a radio that feels larger in the damp light than it did in the office. She grips it like a promise."
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We'll practice three times a week. You'll have the radio by Tuesday, Samir will teach the younger crew how to lock boots on the mud. We'll label every kit. We'll go door to door."
    "Her hand finds yours—callused, warm—and for a second the map of your obligations rearranges itself into a single, human shape. It is small and fierce. It is enough for tonight."
    # [Scene: Tideward Rooftop Garden | Dawn, Two Weeks Later]
    hide samir_reyes
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Bees moving lazily between flowers, the soft clink of mason jars, distant traffic like slow machinery]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm piano notes, a gentle ascending motif]
    "You climb the narrow stair and the city opens—less a skyline of certainty and more a collage of repairs in motion. Hands have made this garden into a breathing room: seedlings in labeled rows, a couple of salvaged chairs, Professor Anika's thermos steaming at the center table."
    show professor_anika_bhat at left:
        zoom 0.7

    professor_anika_bhat "You look like you haven't slept. But your cheeks are healthier than when you showed me that map."
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "That's because the map has wrists now. It moves."

    professor_anika_bhat "Wristed maps are new to me."
    "Nova arrives with a satchel of flyers and a stack of paperwork—legal clinics scheduled, transport plans for families who will need help relocating with dignity. She moves with the efficiency of someone who has learned to convert anger into infrastructure."
    show nova_duarte at center:
        zoom 0.7

    nova_duarte "We got a pro-bono team. They'll be at the community hall tomorrow. We can get guardians for the kids while parents sign the forms. No one goes alone."
    "You notice the way she hesitates when her gaze lands on you—small, quick, nearly invisible. There's a softening there that is not quite trust and not quite surrender. It unsettles you because it feels like history trying to become a different future."

    mara_lin "Thank you. For pushing. And for not letting it all just be noise."

    nova_duarte "Don't be grateful for being noisy. Be grateful for getting things done."

    professor_anika_bhat "Both are required. Surely you know that, Mara."
    "The three of you stand in a messy triangle—science, organizing, and the practical stubbornness that is yours. It is not perfect union. It never will be. But you feel the shape of something that could outlast"
    "any single storm: a coalition that knows how to plant roots and how to sign the right legal waivers."

    menu:
        "Trace the plan on a napkin, draft a public schedule for training groups":
            "You scrub the coffee ring into a neat diagram. Your handwriting is a map someone can follow. Nova nods approval, and Samir starts tallying volunteers."
        "Make tea and listen—let others lead today's meeting":
            "You move to the side with a thermos and a quiet willingness. As the others debate phrasing and dates, you notice gaps you can fill later."
        "Walk the perimeter of the garden and take inventory of seedlings":
            "You wander the planters, counting sprouts and making a mental ledger. The rhythm steadies you; each seedling is a yes."

