    "The scene continues with the group's preparations and the project's progress."
    # [Scene: Solace Harbor Promenade | Afternoon, After Months of Work]
    hide professor_anika_bhat
    hide mara_lin
    hide nova_duarte

    scene bg ch9_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Children playing near a shallow, new tidal pool; vendors calling prices; the distant thrum of construction where the municipal crews build their engineered defenses]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A steady hopeful motif with brass hints—community horns sounding in celebration]
    "There is a storm predicted for the evening—a real one, the kind that used to make your hands search for the compass at your throat as if it could point you to safety. You stand with"
    "Nova and Samir, watching the sky bruise along the horizon. The living breakwater you seeded months ago—rows of marsh and piled oyster shells tied into mesh—ripples like a promise between the open sea and the neighborhood"
    "the city had slated for retreat."
    "You feel your heart begin to race, the old muscle remembering panic. Then Samir slaps a palm to your shoulder."
    show samir_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_reyes "We're ready. Radios checked, evacuation lanes pre-marked. The kids at Block D know the drills. The wetland's at full catch capacity. It's going to do its job."
    "You breathe in: salt, wet tar, the metallic tang of coming rain, and a new scent—people cooking in the market, the solid smell of bread for a household that will not be upended tonight."
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "It's ours tonight, not just the city's model."
    "Nova watches the breakwater with eyes that hold danger and relief in equal measure."
    show nova_duarte at center:
        zoom 0.7

    nova_duarte "We did the right thing—forcing the city into action, then doing the work when they hesitated. It wasn't all pretty, but it kept people."

    mara_lin "Some people still have to leave."

    nova_duarte "Yes. And we'll make sure they go with records, with help, with their histories boxed up so nothing is lost to shame."
    "You think of the families with heirlooms, the alley that folded into salt after the last surge, the small shrine Mrs. Ebbett kept for her grandson. Loss is real. Loss is round and repeatable. But tonight it is measured and chosen, not sudden and forgotten."
    # [Scene: Wetland Pilot Site | Night, The Storm]
    hide samir_reyes
    hide mara_lin
    hide nova_duarte

    scene bg ch9_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The roar of wind, the chorus of strained tarps, people calling over radios; a deep, thrilling sense of exertion]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Crescendoing strings that resolve into an anchored chord]
    "For a long hour you work like your hands have a memory older than your doubts—stacking a supplemental barrier of woven reeds, guiding an elderly neighbor down a pre-lit path, running a radio call for a"
    "missing volunteer. The wetland takes the first of the surge and chews it down into something the shore can hold."
    "When the night finally eases into a drip and then a tired rain, dawn reveals the neighborhood not whole, but standing. The living breakwater has swallowed the worst of the surge. Block D is soaked to"
    "the thresholds, but roofs hold, and families are on their porches, wrapped in borrowed quilts."
    "You sit on the promenade steps, soaked through, and let the exhaustion anchor you. Nova sits at your side, quiet. Words feel too blunt for the relief threading through your bones."
    show nova_duarte at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nova_duarte "I didn't know if we'd pull it off."
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "Neither did I. I only knew I couldn't look at another ledger of promises without action."
    "She turns toward you, the streetlight catching the sea-glass glint at your throat—the brass compass pendant dull with salt."

    nova_duarte "You kept saying 'we' until it meant something."
    "Her hand brushes yours—brief, purposeful. There's a warmth that is not rescue but alliance. It is a kind of intimacy built on shared labor and earned trust, and it makes your throat ache in a steady, human way."
    # [Scene: Tideward Rooftop Garden | Week Later — Small Celebration]
    hide nova_duarte
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Clinking glasses, the scrape of plates, a neighbor singing off-key and being cheered into tune]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: An upbeat acoustic guitar, a melody that lifts and then settles into contentment]
    "You stand with a cup of something warm, watching Samir take a ridiculous, triumphant bow after telling the story of the night the mud ate his boot. Professor Anika recounts the data—confirmed reduction in surge energy"
    "correlated to the restored marsh. The numbers are small but decisive. They mean lives saved tonight, and perhaps fewer forced relocations next season."
    "Mayor Chen's office has grudgingly allocated a small but significant fund for expanded restorative pilots; the municipal liaison you mediated with—bland, professional, and oddly human—has committed staff time to community oversight. Elias Kade is absent from"
    "this moment; the gap where his presence might have been is a patient shape. You do not apologize for it. Some bridges take time to mend."
    "A woman who had helped sew the satchel that carried the legal clinic forms comes up and hands you a small packet: a folded photograph, edges soft with handling. 'From Mrs. Ebbett,' she says. 'She said"
    "she couldn't keep it during the sandbagging. Said it should come back to someone who knows what we did.'"
    "You unfold the photograph: a street of low houses and children chasing kites—an ordinary day. Your chest tightens, and then loosens, as grief and gratitude braid together."
    show professor_anika_bhat at left:
        zoom 0.7

    professor_anika_bhat "To messy victories. To roots that are stubborn enough to take."
    "There is cheering. Nova meets your eyes from across the table, and the look between you now is less about what you were and more about what you are building together—complicated, imperfect, resolutely forward."
    "You think about the families who will still move, the alley that will never be the same. You think about the weight that comes with choosing which homes to save and which to let go. Loss"
    "loops into loss and then—if you work like you mean it—it becomes the scaffolding for something sturdier."
    "You breathe, tasting the steam of the cup, the salt at the corner of your mouth from too many nights outside. The optimism you carry now is not naive; it's callused by cold and grief, but it holds. It is large enough to admit cost and still step forward."
    hide professor_anika_bhat

    scene bg ch9_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A final, rising chord—warm, not triumphant; a promise more than a victory lap]
    "You walk to the edge of the garden and set your hand on the rail. Below, children splash in a shallow pool carved by the new tide flow. Somewhere, in the low bays, the seeded oysters"
    "are doing quieter work, binding the water like stitches. You allow yourself a long, measured smile."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We did it. Not perfectly. Not without cost. But we did it."
    "Nova reaches to tuck a damp curl behind your ear; the gesture is private and ordinary and it steadies you more than any speech. You hold her hand, fingers threading in a way that recognizes there"
    "will be harder choices ahead, but also that you will have allies to face them with."
    show samir_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_reyes "Hey! We're planting a willow on the promenade next week—wanna supervise the shoveling, Mara?"

    mara_lin "Only if you promise to keep your boots out of the seedlings."
    "He salutes with a spoon."
    "You look out at the shoreline—the scarred parts, the mended parts, and the new green lines like stitches sewn by a communal hand. The city is not saved. It is repairing itself, and in the places where repair meets reverence, there is a future you can almost touch."
    "You close your hand around your compass pendant at your throat. It is warm now, warmed by your skin and by the night you spent making something live. You let the hope in—not a bright, naive"
    "flare, but a steady, practical flame that can be used to make maps and plan routes and tuck a photograph into a satchel for safekeeping."
    hide mara_lin
    hide samir_reyes

    scene bg ch9_3be532_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The piano returns, gentle and ascending]
    "You are tired. You are a little broken. You are stubbornly, irrevocably hopeful."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A single gull cries and then is gone; the city exhales]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_9 at full_bg
    "THE END"
